---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'GeoBlue in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'puma-transition', text: 'PUMA Transition Strategy', level: 2 },
  { id: 'visa-compliance', text: 'Visa Compliance', level: 2 },
  { id: 'france-network', text: 'Network Coverage in France', level: 2 },
  { id: 'plans-and-pricing', text: 'Plans and Pricing', level: 2 },
  { id: 'blue-cross-advantage', text: 'Blue Cross Advantage', level: 2 },
  { id: 'who-its-for', text: 'Who Should Choose GeoBlue', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Health Insurance in France', href: '/countries/france/insurance' },
  { title: 'GeoBlue Review', href: '/providers/geoblue' },
  { title: 'GeoBlue vs Aetna', href: '/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue' },
];

const planColumns = [
  { key: 'plan', header: 'Plan' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage' },
  { key: 'francePrice', header: 'France (Age 50)' },
  { key: 'usIncluded', header: 'US Coverage' },
];

const planRows = [
  { plan: 'Voyager Essential', coverage: 'Inpatient + Emergency', francePrice: '€170-230/mo', usIncluded: 'Full BCBS' },
  { plan: 'Voyager Choice', coverage: 'Essential + Outpatient', francePrice: '€230-310/mo', usIncluded: 'Full BCBS' },
  { plan: 'Voyager Excel', coverage: 'Comprehensive + Maternity', francePrice: '€310-420/mo', usIncluded: 'Full BCBS' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'factor', header: 'Factor' },
  { key: 'geoblue', header: 'GeoBlue' },
  { key: 'mutuelle', header: 'PUMA + Mutuelle' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { factor: 'Monthly Cost (Age 50)', geoblue: '€230-310', mutuelle: '€30-150' },
  { factor: 'US Coverage', geoblue: '96% of US hospitals (BCBS)', mutuelle: 'None' },
  { factor: 'Coverage Level', geoblue: '100% worldwide', mutuelle: '~100% in France' },
  { factor: 'Pre-existing', geoblue: 'Varies by plan', mutuelle: 'Full coverage' },
  { factor: 'Wait Time', geoblue: 'Immediate', mutuelle: '6-9 months from arrival' },
  { factor: 'Mobile App', geoblue: 'Excellent', mutuelle: 'Varies' },
  { factor: 'Best For', geoblue: 'US expats, BCBS familiar', mutuelle: 'Long-term residents' },
];

const hospitalColumns = [
  { key: 'city', header: 'City' },
  { key: 'hospitals', header: 'Private Hospitals' },
  { key: 'directBilling', header: 'Direct Billing' },
];

const hospitalRows = [
  { city: 'Paris', hospitals: 'American Hospital of Paris, Hôpital Américain, Clinique Turin', directBilling: true },
  { city: 'Paris Region', hospitals: 'Clinique des Champs-Élysées, Hôpital Privé des Peupliers', directBilling: 'Verify' },
  { city: 'Lyon', hospitals: 'Clinique du Parc, Hôpital Privé Jean Mermoz', directBilling: 'Verify' },
  { city: 'Nice/Riviera', hospitals: 'Centre Hospitalier Princesse Grace (Monaco), Clinique Saint-George', directBilling: 'Verify' },
  { city: 'Bordeaux', hospitals: 'Clinique Saint-Martin, Polyclinique Bordeaux Nord', directBilling: 'Verify' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="GeoBlue Health Insurance in France"
  description="Guide to using GeoBlue in France. Blue Cross Blue Shield network for US expats. Visa compliance, PUMA transition, and pricing."
  headline="GeoBlue Health Insurance in France"
  subheadline="Blue Cross Blue Shield's international arm. Keep your familiar US network while enjoying la vie française."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/countries/france-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get a GeoBlue France Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/geoblue"
>
  <h2 id="overview">GeoBlue in France</h2>
  <p>
    GeoBlue is Blue Cross Blue Shield's international brand, designed specifically for Americans abroad. For US expats in France—retirees, remote workers, and those seeking the French lifestyle—GeoBlue offers continuity with the US healthcare system they know.
  </p>
  <p>
    France requires private insurance for visa applications, and you can't access PUMA (public healthcare) for 6-9 months after arrival. GeoBlue fills this gap while providing the Blue Cross network access Americans are familiar with.
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">96%</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">US hospitals in network</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">€30K+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Exceeds visa minimum</p>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4 text-center">
      <p class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary-600">190+</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Countries covered</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Get a France-Specific Quote"
    description="See what GeoBlue costs for Americans in France."
    buttonText="Get Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/geoblue"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="puma-transition">PUMA Transition Strategy</h2>
  <p>
    France's PUMA (Protection Universelle Maladie) provides excellent public healthcare after 3+ months of residency. But enrollment processing takes another 3-6 months. Here's how to plan your coverage:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">The Timeline</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li><strong>Months 1-3:</strong> GeoBlue required (no PUMA eligibility)</li>
      <li><strong>Month 3:</strong> Apply for PUMA enrollment</li>
      <li><strong>Months 3-9:</strong> Continue GeoBlue while PUMA processes</li>
      <li><strong>Month 6-9:</strong> Receive Carte Vitale, decide on transition</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>GeoBlue's Role</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Visa-compliant coverage from day one</li>
    <li>Full protection during 6-9 month PUMA wait</li>
    <li>24/7 English support while navigating French bureaucracy</li>
    <li>Blue Cross network for trips back to the US</li>
    <li>Mobile app for finding care and filing claims</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>After PUMA Enrollment</h3>
  <p>
    Once enrolled in PUMA, most expats switch to the French system:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>PUMA (Sécurité Sociale):</strong> Covers ~70% of medical costs</li>
    <li><strong>Mutuelle:</strong> €30-150/month top-up for the remaining ~30%</li>
    <li><strong>Total:</strong> Significantly cheaper than international insurance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some American expats keep GeoBlue alongside PUMA specifically for US coverage when visiting family.
  </p>

  <h2 id="visa-compliance">Visa Compliance</h2>
  <p>
    France's VLS-TS Visiteur visa (the main non-working visa for expats) has specific insurance requirements:
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">French Visa Insurance Requirements</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
      <li>Minimum €30,000 medical coverage</li>
      <li>Hospitalization and emergency care included</li>
      <li>Medical evacuation and repatriation coverage</li>
      <li>Valid for entire intended stay</li>
      <li>Visa letter from insurer confirming coverage</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>Does GeoBlue Meet These Requirements?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. GeoBlue Voyager plans provide comprehensive coverage well above France's €30,000 minimum. GeoBlue is experienced with visa documentation for French applications.
  </p>

  <h3>Visa Documentation</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue provides:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Certificate of coverage confirming amounts exceed €30,000</li>
    <li>Policy validity dates matching your visa request</li>
    <li>Coverage territory confirmation including France</li>
    <li>Contact information for consulate verification</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="france-network">Network Coverage in France</h2>
  <p>
    France has excellent private healthcare, especially in Paris and major cities.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={hospitalColumns} rows={hospitalRows} />
  </div>

  <h3>The American Hospital of Paris</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue's standout France facility is the American Hospital of Paris (Hôpital Américain de Paris). This JCI-accredited hospital offers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Fully bilingual English/French staff</li>
    <li>American-trained physicians</li>
    <li>US-style care approach</li>
    <li>Direct billing with GeoBlue</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>GeoBlue Mobile App</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue's app is particularly useful in France:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GPS-based provider search in any French city</li>
    <li>Filter by specialty and language (English-speaking)</li>
    <li>Digital insurance card always available</li>
    <li>Claims submission from your phone</li>
    <li>Real-time eligibility verification</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Outside Paris</h3>
  <p>
    French healthcare costs are regulated and reasonable:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>GP visit: €25-50</li>
    <li>Specialist: €50-150</li>
    <li>Hospital day: €300-800</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Pay upfront and submit claims via the app. Reimbursement is typically processed within 10-15 business days.
  </p>

  <h2 id="plans-and-pricing">Plans and Pricing</h2>
  <p>
    GeoBlue Voyager plans include US coverage—not an expensive add-on.
  </p>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={planColumns} rows={planRows} />
  </div>

  <p>
    <em>Prices include worldwide coverage with full Blue Cross US access. Age 50 shown.</em>
  </p>

  <h3>Plan Recommendations for France</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Voyager Essential:</strong> Hospital-focused. Good for visa compliance if you'll use French healthcare for routine care.</li>
    <li><strong>Voyager Choice:</strong> Most popular. Includes outpatient for full protection during the PUMA wait.</li>
    <li><strong>Voyager Excel:</strong> Comprehensive including maternity. Best for families or those planning significant healthcare needs.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Deductible Strategy</h3>
  <p>
    Since you'll likely transition to PUMA within a year, consider your risk tolerance:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Higher deductible ($2,000-5,000) reduces premiums for temporary coverage</li>
    <li>French healthcare is affordable—routine care manageable out-of-pocket</li>
    <li>Lower deductible if you have ongoing health concerns during transition</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="blue-cross-advantage">Blue Cross Advantage</h2>
  <p>
    The core reason to choose GeoBlue for France:
  </p>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">US Network Benefits</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
        <li>96% of US hospitals in network</li>
        <li>Blue Cross negotiated rates</li>
        <li>Direct billing—no claims in the US</li>
        <li>Familiar BCBS network</li>
        <li>Keep relationships with US doctors</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Why It Matters</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Paris is 8 hours from NYC by air</li>
        <li>Many US expats visit family annually</li>
        <li>US specialists accessible for second opinions</li>
        <li>Medicare doesn't work abroad</li>
        <li>Seamless if you eventually return</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>Medicare Replacement</h3>
  <p>
    US Medicare provides no coverage in France (or almost anywhere abroad). For American retirees in France, GeoBlue replaces Medicare during your pre-PUMA period and provides US coverage for visits home that PUMA can't offer.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Blue Cross Coverage in France"
    description="Keep your familiar US network while living abroad."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/geoblue"
  />

  <h2 id="who-its-for">Who Should Choose GeoBlue</h2>

  <div class="my-8 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />
  </div>

  <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Ideal For</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
        <li>US citizens moving to France</li>
        <li>Those familiar with Blue Cross</li>
        <li>VLS-TS Visiteur visa applicants</li>
        <li>Pre-PUMA transition period (first 6-9 months)</li>
        <li>Expats who visit the US regularly</li>
        <li>Anyone wanting the largest US network</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Consider Alternatives</h3>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-600">
        <li>Non-US citizens (can't purchase GeoBlue)</li>
        <li>Budget-focused (French mutuelles cheaper long-term)</li>
        <li>Already PUMA-enrolled (mutuelle more practical)</li>
        <li>Those who never visit the US</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3>US Totalization Agreement Note</h3>
  <p>
    If you're sent to France by a US employer, you may be ineligible for PUMA for up to 5 years under the US-France totalization agreement. In this case, GeoBlue becomes your primary insurance for much longer than the typical 6-9 month transition.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <h3>Do I need to be a US citizen for GeoBlue?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. GeoBlue requires US citizenship or permanent residency with US ties. It's designed specifically for Americans abroad. Non-US citizens should consider Aetna, AXA, or other international insurers.
  </p>

  <h3>Is GeoBlue accepted for French visa applications?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. GeoBlue provides coverage exceeding the €30,000 minimum and supplies the documentation French consulates require.
  </p>

  <h3>Should I keep GeoBlue after I get my Carte Vitale?</h3>
  <p>
    Most expats switch to PUMA + mutuelle, which is significantly cheaper. However, if you visit the US regularly or want to maintain Blue Cross coverage, you could keep GeoBlue as a supplement.
  </p>

  <h3>How does GeoBlue compare to Aetna for France?</h3>
  <p>
    Both are excellent for US expats with integrated US coverage. GeoBlue offers the Blue Cross network; Aetna offers modular Navigator plans. Similar pricing and coverage—choose based on network preference. <a href="/compare/aetna-international-vs-geoblue">See our comparison</a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How does GeoBlue compare to French mutuelles?</h3>
  <p>
    GeoBlue costs more (€230-420/month vs. €30-150/month for mutuelle) but offers worldwide coverage and US network access. Mutuelles only supplement French public care—they don't cover you abroad or in the US.
  </p>

  <h3>Can GeoBlue cover the 6-9 month PUMA wait?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. This is the primary use case. Start GeoBlue before your move, use it during the transition, then decide whether to keep it for US coverage or fully transition to PUMA + mutuelle.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready for Coverage in France?"
    description="Get a personalized GeoBlue quote for your France move."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/geoblue"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. French visa requirements, PUMA enrollment rules, and insurance policies change. We are not insurance brokers, immigration consultants, or tax advisors. Verify all information with the French consulate, CPAM, and GeoBlue before making decisions.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
